        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    The key is using the greenhouse as a temporary buffer, not a permanent environment.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Mini Greenhouse for Hardening Off</h2>

  <h3>1. Ventilation</h3>
  <p>
    Airflow is critical. A greenhouse that cannot open easily is much harder to use safely during hardening off.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Easy Access</h3>
  <p>
    You will be moving plants in and out or adjusting exposure frequently. The setup should make that easy.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Light Diffusion</h3>
  <p>
    Slightly filtered light can help reduce shock early in the process.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Temperature Control (Passive)</h3>
  <p>
    The structure should not trap excessive heat during sunny conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Size That Matches Your Trays</h3>
  <p>
    A good fit makes daily handling simpler and reduces stress during transitions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Fully Closed Mini Greenhouses Can Cause Problems</h2>

  <p>
    One of the most common mistakes is leaving a mini greenhouse fully closed during hardening off.
  </p>

  <p>
    In direct sun, temperatures inside can rise quickly, sometimes far beyond what seedlings can tolerate. At the same time, airflow is reduced, which limits the strengthening effect seedlings need.
  </p>

  <p>
    For hardening off, more openness is usually better than more protection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Mini Greenhouse vs Open-Air Hardening Off</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Mini greenhouse:</strong> buffers conditions and reduces stress early.</li>
    <li><strong>Open air:</strong> provides full exposure needed before transplanting.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Most gardeners benefit from using both approaches at different stages of the process.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/best-setup-for-hardening-off-seedlings/">best setup for hardening off seedlings</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Use a Mini Greenhouse for Hardening Off</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Start with short outdoor exposure inside a ventilated greenhouse.</li>
    <li>Gradually increase exposure time each day.</li>
    <li>Open vents or remove covers as conditions allow.</li>
    <li>Transition to partial and then full open-air exposure.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The goal is to reduce protection over time, not maintain it.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overdo</h2>

  <p>
    Many gardeners try to protect seedlings too much during hardening off. This can delay adaptation and lead to weaker plants when they are finally exposed fully.
  </p>

  <p>
    A mini greenhouse should support the transition, not replace it.
  </p>
</section>

