</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Using a Mini Greenhouse</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Keeping it fully closed in sunlight.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Using it too long into the hardening process.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Not increasing exposure gradually.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Assuming protection equals success.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best results come from controlled exposure, not maximum protection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    For most hardening-off setups, use a mini greenhouse that can open easily and provide ventilation. Start with partial protection, then gradually increase exposure by opening the structure or moving seedlings into open air.
  </p>

  <p>
    Avoid fully enclosed setups in warm or sunny conditions. In most cases, the best mini greenhouse is one that helps you transition away from it over time.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The goal is not to keep seedlings protected — it is to help them adapt.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best mini greenhouse for hardening off seedlings is one that allows controlled exposure to outdoor conditions while avoiding excessive heat and poor airflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most gardeners, that means choosing a ventilated, easy-to-adjust structure and using it as a temporary tool during the transition process. As seedlings adapt, the greenhouse becomes less necessary, and full outdoor exposure becomes the goal.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Use the greenhouse to ease the transition, then step away from it as plants toughen up.
  </p>
</section>